    <p><xref ref="sec-ai-backstory"/> was developed using public domain and openly licensed resources. The historical overview draws upon <url href="https://nij.ojp.gov/topics/articles/brief-history-artificial-intelligence">A Brief History of Artificial Intelligence</url>, published by the National Institute of Justice (NIJ). As a publication of the United States federal government, this work is in the public domain under 17 U.S.C. § 105 and may be freely reused and adapted, making it fully compatible with the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0) license under which this textbook is distributed. This section was also informed by <url href="https://infobooks.org/pdfview/introduction-to-artificial-intelligence-microsoft-and-wttc-842/">Introduction to Artificial Intelligence</url>, authored by Microsoft and the World Travel &amp; Tourism Council (WTTC). The original publication includes a copyright notice that permits redistribution under specified conditions but requires that the content not be amended. Accordingly, this textbook uses the publication as a reference for background information and organization rather than adapting or modifying its copyrighted text. The original work therefore remains under its own licensing terms, while the original text for this textbook is distributed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0) license.</p>

  <p><xref ref="sec-characterizing-intelligence"/> was developed using several openly licensed educational resources. Portions of this section were adapted from <url href="https://milnepublishing.geneseo.edu/future-is-now/chapter/understanding-artificial-intelligence/">Understanding Artificial Intelligence</url>, by Jason S. Wrench and Sanae Elmoudden, published by Milne Open Textbooks, and from <url href="https://alliedmedia.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/peoples-guide-ai.pdf">A People's Guide to AI</url>, by Mimi Onuoha and Diana Nucera. Additional inspiration was drawn from <url href="https://www.csfieldguide.org.nz/en/chapters/artificial-intelligence/chatterbots-and-the-turing-test/">Chatterbots and the Turing Test</url>, published by the Computer Science Field Guide (CSFG). <em>Understanding Artificial Intelligence</em> and <em>A People's Guide to AI</em> are licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution–NonCommercial–ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0) license and permit adaptation with attribution. The material incorporated into this textbook has been revised, reorganized, and expanded to fit its learning objectives, terminology, and style. The original sources remain under their respective licenses, while the original text written for this textbook is distributed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0) license.</p>

